3.7 Ethical and professional issue: patron data and purpose limitation
Circulation data can reveal what a person reads, researches, questions, or fears. A technically useful database can therefore create professional and legal risk. The question is not merely whether staff can store a field, but whether the institution needs it for a legitimate, explained purpose.
The Philippine Data Privacy Act establishes principles including transparency, legitimate purpose, and proportionality (Republic of the Philippines 2012; National Privacy Commission 2023). In database design, these principles become concrete:

collect only fields necessary for a defined service;
separate identity data from analysis data where possible;
restrict access by role and review privileges;
protect exports, temporary files, backups, and test databases;
define retention and disposal for accounts, loans, logs, and audit trails;
use fictional or properly de-identified data for teaching and testing;
document data sharing with vendors and institutional offices; and
provide processes for appropriate access and correction.

De-identification is not simply deleting names. A combination of course, rare patron category, branch, date, and title may still identify someone. Aggregation can reduce risk, but very small counts may remain revealing.
The IFLA ethics framework connects privacy and confidentiality with equitable access and intellectual freedom (International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions 2012). Retaining every borrowing history “in case it becomes useful” can chill inquiry and increase breach harm. At the same time, deleting data without records policy can weaken accountability. The responsible approach defines purpose, minimum data, authorized access, retention, secure disposal, and documented exceptions.
Database administrators and vendors require enough access to maintain systems, but technical capability does not create unlimited professional permission. Audit logs should support accountability without becoming a second, poorly governed surveillance dataset.

Ethical checkpoint. A dean requests a list of students who borrowed materials on a controversial topic. What questions should the library ask about authority, purpose, necessity, intellectual freedom, privacy, and less intrusive alternatives?

6.7 Ethical and professional issue: ranking, privacy, and representational harm
Discovery systems distribute attention. A result on the first page is more likely to be read, cited, purchased, or remembered than a result on page twenty. Ranking therefore has professional consequences even when no person intends discrimination.
Bias can enter through several routes. Collections reflect historical funding and exclusion. Metadata may use outdated, colonial, stigmatizing, or externally imposed language. Full-text availability can boost well-funded publishers over local print sources. Usage-based ranking can amplify what already receives attention. English-language test queries can make other languages appear less relevant. Vendor coverage agreements may be invisible to users. Automated query expansion, recommendation, and generative summaries can add further opacity.
The professional response is not to promise a neutral system. It is to establish accountable discovery:

document corpus scope, important exclusions, and update schedules;
maintain provenance when description is corrected or supplemented;
test named user tasks across languages, devices, and access conditions;
include affected communities in terminology and interface decisions;
distinguish organic relevance, configured boosts, sponsored placement, and recommendations;
provide routes for reporting harmful description and broken access;
retain query logs only when necessary, minimize identifiers, restrict access, and set deletion rules;
require vendor explanations of coverage, ranking controls, analytics, and data reuse;
keep human review for high-impact automated changes.

Search logs deserve special care. They can expose health concerns, political interests, religious questions, identities, locations, and research plans. The Philippine Data Privacy Act requires lawful, proportionate handling of personal information, and discovery analytics should follow purpose limitation and data minimization rather than collecting every available signal (Republic of the Philippines 2012; National Privacy Commission 2023). A useful dashboard does not justify indefinite storage of identifiable queries.

Professional judgment prompt: A vendor offers “better personalization” if the library sends persistent user identifiers and complete search histories. What evidence would justify the benefit, what data could be avoided, how long would records be retained, and what nonpersonalized option would remain?

7.7 Ethical and professional issue: automation bias and accountable intervention
Automation changes authority. A value produced by a script may look consistent and therefore trustworthy even when the rule is incomplete. Automation bias occurs when people give undue weight to automated output or fail to investigate contradictory evidence. In metadata work, this can turn a convenient mapping into widespread representational harm.
Consider a script that infers creator nationality from names, assigns gender from honorifics, translates Indigenous terms without community review, or labels rights based only on publication year. Each operation may be technically possible. None is professionally justified without reliable evidence, a legitimate purpose, documented uncertainty, and appropriate authority.
AI-assisted coding introduces a second layer. A generative system can suggest R syntax, explanations, mappings, or regular expressions, but plausible code may call nonexistent functions, mishandle missing values, expose data to an external service, or encode a policy the user did not intend. AI-generated code must be treated as untrusted draft code: review it line by line, test it on known cases, inspect dependencies, and never supply restricted records to a service without authorization and data-protection review.
Accountable automation includes:

a stated service problem and responsible owner;
documented source, scope, rule authority, assumptions, and exclusions;
minimum necessary data and controlled access;
preserved source values and reversible outputs;
tests covering multilingual, missing, boundary, and adversarial cases;
visible exception handling rather than forced conformity;
logs proportionate to the task and protected by retention rules;
peer review for high-impact transformations;
a way for affected users or communities to challenge results;
monitoring after deployment and a defined stop condition.

Privacy obligations apply to scripts as much as to databases. A temporary CSV copied to a personal cloud folder can create a breach even if the code is correct. Under the Philippine Data Privacy Act, processing must have a legitimate purpose and use proportionate safeguards (Republic of the Philippines 2012; National Privacy Commission 2023). Test with synthetic or de-identified data when possible, and do not place secrets, passwords, or API keys inside source code.

Professional judgment prompt: A script can assign subject headings to 80% of new records with 92% agreement against a past dataset. What does this statistic fail to tell you? Which records require review, who can contest a heading, and what evidence would justify moving from suggestion to automatic assignment?

8.7 Ethical and professional issue: linkage, consent, and contextual integrity
Linked data can make relationships visible, but visibility is not always harmless. Connecting an archival name to a current identity, a historical address to a household, or a community object to a sacred place can expose people or knowledge beyond the context in which information was provided. Public availability in one database does not automatically justify aggregation, enrichment, or republication in another.
APIs also make extraction scalable. A website intended for individual lookup may expose an API that enables bulk profiling. Technical access is not the same as ethical permission. Professionals must examine law, license, consent, expectations, community protocols, and the consequences of combination.
Responsible API and linked-data practice includes:

collect only fields necessary for the stated service;
distinguish identifiers, assertions, labels, and inferred links;
record source, retrieval time, transformation, license, and confidence;
retain local or community-preferred description when external links are added;
avoid publishing precise sensitive locations or personal relationships without authority;
provide correction, unlinking, and takedown routes;
test for language, geographic, historical, and collection bias;
do not expose API keys, tokens, patron identifiers, or query histories;
review vendor reuse, analytics, retention, and cross-border processing;
design a fallback when an external API changes or disappears.

The Philippine Data Privacy Act applies when linked datasets contain personal information, including when separate fields become identifying through combination (Republic of the Philippines 2012; National Privacy Commission 2023). Data minimization and purpose limitation should guide both requests and published outputs.
Machine-generated links require particular care. Entity reconciliation may assign a confidence score, but a high score is not evidence of consent or community acceptance. Namesakes, transliteration, changing boundaries, and organizational succession create plausible false matches. Use automated matching to produce candidates, preserve alternatives, and require appropriate review for consequential links.

Professional judgment prompt: A genealogy API can connect digitized school registers to living family trees. What lawful purpose, consent, time limits, access restrictions, accuracy controls, and community consultation would be required before a library enabled the connection?

9.7 Ethical and professional issue: surveillance, dark patterns, and digital exclusion
UX research and analytics can improve services, but they can also become surveillance. Search queries, click paths, account events, device details, locations, recordings, and session replays may reveal health, political, religious, legal, academic, or identity-related interests. Collecting data because a tool offers it is not a legitimate research purpose.
Ethical UX research requires a specific question, informed consent where appropriate, minimum necessary data, secure storage, limited access, a retention schedule, and reporting that avoids re-identification. Participants must know they may stop. Researchers should not record passwords, patron records, or unrelated screen content. The Philippine Data Privacy Act’s principles of transparency, legitimate purpose, and proportionality apply to research and analytics (Republic of the Philippines 2012; National Privacy Commission 2023).
Dark patterns are interface choices that manipulate people toward actions that benefit the service provider rather than the user. Examples include making privacy-protective options difficult to find, using confusing consent language, preselecting broad data sharing, disguising advertising as search results, or making account deletion harder than account creation. Libraries should not reproduce these practices through vendor defaults.
Digital exclusion also occurs when a service assumes current smartphones, stable broadband, individual email accounts, English fluency, credit cards, or comfort with identity verification. Offering an “accessible alternative” through a slower, stigmatizing, or staff-dependent route may preserve formal access while denying equal independence.
Professional safeguards include:

include disabled and marginalized users throughout planning and evaluation;
provide accessible participation and fair compensation;
minimize analytics and disable invasive replay by default;
separate service improvement data from patron profiling;
retain raw recordings only as long as necessary;
explain personalization and allow nonpersonalized use;
require accessibility, privacy, performance, and exit clauses in procurement;
publish accessible contact, correction, and complaint channels;
maintain offline or assisted routes without making them inferior;
report limitations and populations not represented in a study.


Professional judgment prompt: A vendor offers session recordings showing every tap, keystroke, and form entry. What research question could justify any part of this collection, which fields must be masked or excluded, who may view recordings, and when must they be deleted?

10.7 Ethical and professional issue: preservation rights, privacy, and sustainable custody
Preserving a digital object can conflict with access restrictions, privacy, copyright, community authority, and the right to be forgotten or to restrict harmful exposure. Copying, migration, decryption, format analysis, and cloud replication are preservation actions, but technical necessity does not automatically provide legal or ethical authority.
Archives may hold records containing personal addresses, health information, political activity, disciplinary records, or names of vulnerable people. Cultural collections may contain sacred or restricted knowledge. Cloud replication can move data into additional jurisdictions and expose it to provider personnel or legal demands. Encryption protects some risks but complicates key preservation; losing the key can make intact copies permanently inaccessible.
Responsible stewardship includes:

document authority for preservation copying, transformation, and access;
separate preservation retention from public availability;
classify sensitive content and apply proportionate access controls;
minimize cloud metadata that can reveal identities or collection sensitivity;
record embargoes, community protocols, takedown, and review dates;
maintain key custody, recovery, rotation, and authorized destruction;
obtain deletion evidence when retention authority ends;
assess vendor location, subcontractors, incident reporting, and data reuse;
budget for ongoing custody rather than launching unfunded collections;
consult affected communities about significant properties and acceptable access.

Under the Philippine Data Privacy Act, long-term retention of personal information still requires lawful purpose, proportionality, security, and retention discipline (Republic of the Philippines 2012; National Privacy Commission 2023). “For preservation” should not become an unlimited exemption from governance.
Environmental sustainability is also professional. Multiple copies, computation, media replacement, and cloud storage consume energy and materials. The response is not to abandon redundancy, but to appraise responsibly, avoid uncontrolled duplication, choose appropriate storage tiers, monitor actual use, and include environmental cost in stewardship decisions.

Professional judgment prompt: A donor gives a hard drive of community photographs with no agreements and asks the archive to “keep everything forever in the cloud.” What must be clarified before copying, identifying, uploading, or providing access?

12.8 Ethical and professional issue: datafication, small groups, and the authority of metrics
Datafication is the transformation of activities and relationships into data for monitoring, prediction, or control. Libraries can improve services through data, but not everything valuable should be measured at the individual level. Privacy, intellectual freedom, dignity, care, cultural meaning, and trust can be damaged by excessive measurement.
Metrics gain authority when presented in dashboards, rankings, or AI summaries. A target can redirect work toward what is counted. If staff are judged by ticket closure, complex questions may be rushed. If collections are judged by downloads, locally important but smaller-language materials may lose support. If an algorithm predicts “low engagement,” people facing access barriers may receive fewer services.
Small-group analysis is especially sensitive. Disaggregation may reveal inequity, yet publishing a table with two users can expose identity. Suppression can protect privacy but erase evidence of marginalization. The response requires purpose, community consultation, minimum necessary detail, controlled access, uncertainty, and complementary qualitative evidence.
AI does not remove these duties. Automated summaries can fabricate explanations, hide missingness, infer sensitive traits, and present correlations as causes. Treat AI-generated analysis as untrusted draft work. Preserve source data, inspect code and transformations, verify every claim, disclose material use, and never upload restricted data without authorization.
Responsible evidence practice includes:

collect only what a stated decision requires;
preserve provenance and definitions;
let communities contest categories and interpretations;
use aggregation and access controls proportionately;
report denominators, missingness, uncertainty, and limitations;
pair performance measures with equity and quality measures;
avoid individual ranking when service improvement can use aggregate evidence;
set retention and metric-retirement rules;
document when evidence does not justify action;
evaluate unintended effects after implementation.


Professional judgment prompt: A university proposes a “student success score” combining library visits, database use, borrowing, and help requests. What assumptions, privacy and intellectual-freedom harms, missing contexts, false inferences, and less intrusive alternatives must be examined?
